      "content": "It sounds like you're dealing with a memory leak that's not immediately apparent. In that case, you can try to instrument your code to track memory allocation and deallocation more explicitly.\n\nOne approach is to use a custom memory tracking mechanism, such as a simple array to keep track of allocated memory blocks. You can add a function that increments a counter every time memory is allocated, and decrements it every time it's deallocated. This can help you identify where the memory is being allocated and deallocated.\n\nAnother approach is to use a \"memory snapshot\" technique, where you periodically take a snapshot of the heap and print out the addresses and sizes of all allocated memory blocks. You can use a simple function like `malloc` or `new` to allocate memory, and then use `free` or `delete` to deallocate it. This can help you identify any memory blocks that are being allocated but not deallocated.\n\nIn your case, since you're using `new` to allocate memory for the buffer, you can try to instrument the `telemetry_module.send` function to track memory allocation. You can add a function that prints out the address and size of the allocated memory block, and then call that function from `telemetry_module",
